					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">Jagasian wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I'm definitely interested in status reports, and we all understand that things may go nowhere, may take a long time, etc, as this is something that you are doing in your spare time... so fire away.</div>
<br />
<br />OK, here goes.  I haven't updated my page at all (lazy <img src="./images/smilies/icon_smile.gif" alt=":-)" title="Smile" />  but I've been hard at work.
<br />
<br />I'm fairly confident in saying that the NES core is 100% accurate now, and I've run over 4000 ROMs through it.  It supports 213 mappers now (more with "sub mappers", but 213 NES mapper numbers).  The chip is 96% full, and I need to move up to the next size chip I think.  Every single Blargg test passes 100%, every timing test I've made, and every CPU test I've made are all a go.  I have 2 more "possibly wrong" games to test now... I had three but I bought one of them off of ebay and surprise surprise, it does the same thing on the NES as it does the FPGA.  I suspect the other two games will be similar.
<br />
<br />
<br />I was working on getting all the mappers refined and tested, which I did during the large ROM tests I performed.  So, I'm pretty sure the ROMs are as good as they're gonna get for now.  
<br />
<br />The ines V2.00 thing is hot right now because I'm at the perfect point where it is easy to add and it will simplify things greatly, so I hope to get that finalized so I can flesh it out some more.  Once people think it's a good idea I will move and define all the submapper things and post a list and all that.  
<br />
<br />The hardware has reached the end of its useful life, and I am working on the final production prototype of the hardware.  The "back end" (NES playing) part is all finished now, and I just need to work on the front end now, which is the user interface, game loading, etc.   Currently it uses USB and a windows host program to send data and debug and all that.
<br />
<br />The hardware's going to get much smaller (I want the footprint of an NES cart or a tad bigger) and it will be vastly simplified.  Controllers will be all USB based, so I do not need lots of hardware to support weird controllers and stuff.
<br />
<br />Once the front end is done, I will be in a better position to make more consoles for it.  The first addition will be PAL NES, which should be pretty simple, and then Atari 2600.  I have the complete chip schematics for the RIOT and TIA, so that will be relatively simple to do I suspect.  From there, it's up in the air.
<br />
<br />Ideally, I want at least 3 different consoles supported before I attempt to go into production.  We'll see what happens once I get that done.  Speaking of production, the cost of the FPGAs went through the floor, and with my china connection, the cost could be well within range of what people are willing to spend.</div>

					
